,"1335":"1335","1367":"1367","1453":"1453","1288":"1288","1320":"1320","1375":"1375","about 1335":"about 1335","about 1357":"about 1357","about 1350":"about 1350","Lowther Castle, Askham, Westmorland, England":"Lowther Castle, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom","Wythop, Cumberland, England":"Wythop, Cumberland, England","Workington, Cumberland, England":"Workington, Cumberland, England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lowther","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Cumbria, so called from the river on which it stands. The placename is of obscure etymology, perhaps of ancient Welsh origin (compare   Lauder  ), or from Old Norse <i>lauthr</i> ‘froth, foam’ + <i>á</i> ‘river’."],"variants":[{"name":"Lawther","meanings":["Scottish, northern Irish, and northern English: variant of   Lowther   and   Lauder  ."]},{"name":"Lauder","meanings":["Scottish (Borders): habitational name from Lauder in Berwickshire, originally a name for the river Leader (itself from British <i>lou-</i> + <i>dubro-</i> ‘cleansing river’). Compare   Lauderdale  ."]},{"name":"Lattea","meanings":["Altered form of English   Lowther  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":